args: There's only one possible reason why\nnobody has managed to heal him.
He doesn't WANT to be healed.
As you know, his heart once broke from all\nthe suffering his father inflicted on him.
It's clear just from looking at him.
But somewhere deep down, Hanabusa\nrefuses to accept it.
He's still forging onward as if nothing\never happened. Right, Hanabusa?

But even if his heart wants to keep going,
his body doesn't have the strength. That
disconnect is what causes his stomach
pains.
So even if he SAYS he wants to be healed,\nnothing you try will take—because deep\ndown, he's resisting it all.
Your support made me so happy, Aeleen.
It was pure bliss to live surrounded by\nnature, dancing only when I wanted to.
But all the while, part of me continued\nto cry out for the stage, no matter what\npain I knew I would have to endure.
Because that is the only path that\nwill let me become like the moon.
Listen, you can't keep forcing yourself to—
As I feared! Can you fight, Hanabusa?
I can. I care not for my own suffering.
Witness a dance from Hinomoto—\nthe sprout that parts the snow!

The young shoot shrivels 'neath the weight
of heavy snow,

the warmth of spring a thousand miles away.

Yet even after wilting, it dreams an everlasting
dream...

...of spring's glorious arrival.
The first is defeated. Ugh... My stomach...
One day, I will part the snow with my\nown two hands!
He still believes in the story of the sprout\nthat parts the snow.
That one day, he will be the one to usher\nin the warmth of spring.
But what if he doesn't LAST that long?!
What if the shoot is unable to withstand\nthe weight and the cold? If it withers?
He's your retainer! Isn't he important to\nyou? Why won't you DO something?!
He is indeed. And if he withers...
Then I'll feel sad, and say that I saw\nthis coming.
You honestly wouldn't regret your inaction?
I'm sure I would. But he and I would share\nthose regrets together.
He's decided on the life he wants to live.\nI've decided simply to watch over him.
When he falls into the depths, I'll fall with\nhim. That's what it means to be master\nand servant.
Now, finish this, Hanabusa!\nYou'll get not a shred of help from me!
I can't say that doesn't sting, but I\nwouldn't want to trouble you either way!
Good job. All right, we shouldn't run into\nany more fiends on the way to the venue.\nLet's get moving.

You see this through to the end—no
matter how much it exhausts you.
And if you dance even slightly better
than last time, we'll call it a victory.
I will neither fail nor falter—even if\nI have to crawl to the finish line.
Don't worry. All I wanted to say was...
Do your best! I'll be cheering you on.
You're off to perform the sacred offering\ndance to Amaterasu in Hinomoto, then?\nTake care, and good luck!
Yes. I must take my leave of you for some\ntime, but I promise to return with good\ntidings.
Be well in my absence,\nLady Mitsuhide.
Just give it a shot. If you have fun,\nthat's all that matters. Later.
I'm sure it'll go well. He's become a lot\nstronger since coming here—he's bound\nto succeed.
What? It's going to be a disaster.\nHe'll come back crying, for sure.
Hey, I only say that because I know the\nguy better than a block of sharp cheddar.
Be sure to give him a warm welcome when\nhe comes back all crestfallen, okay?
But don't worry! Failure only serves to\nenrich his character. That's how he works.
